In the meanwhile, I asked my friend who used virtualenvwrapper with hooks... but apparently he doensn't use hooks anymore :/

Also, I found an use case for setting environment variables as well, but it was an instance of ""cumbersome app configuration"" that could have been (and was!) fixed by using sane defaults.

I'm not sure yet what would be the problem with the string interpolation that you mentioned, but I only skimmed the proposed changes. But if we both agree that doing it in python code is the way forward I'll pick that. At least now I know which usecases (just the env variables) for more than 1 person I can/have to cover.

I'll probably use something like the `VIRTUALENVWRAPPER_HOOK_DIR` (defaulting to `WORKON_HOME`) for the location of the hooks/customization

That file name could be something like `user_scripts.py`, `user.py`, `hooks.py` or something else

There'd be one such global file, and one for each env, and the file would probably look like this:

```python

env = {
  'CUSTOM_VAR': 'VAL'
}

def get_env_details(env):
  yadayada

def preactivate(env):
  yadayada


@priority(20)
def postrmvirtualenv(env):
  yadayada

```

I was thinking of using `@priority` to let the user specify in which order some hooks should be executed, rather than simply defining that the global hooks will be overridden (or executed before) the per-env hooks. but this latter alternative might be better

Also, obviously setting the environment variables can clash with the `.bashrc` (or the like) that gets sourced/executed by the subshell, but hopefully users should be aware of that and usually just define extra variables (rather than redefining things like `PATH`)

To execute random scripts/program, `subprocess.call` should be enough, so I don't plan to implicitly allow anything else than python scripts as hooks/program to be executed

This is just a quick comment that I wanted to write down. I've been quite busy lately, but this change is definitely one of the most interesting for me",{},,User,False
