1222,IssueCommentEvent,2015-02-23 21:40:35+00:00,31230734,jaraco/keyring,308610,jaraco,,,58653140,75640428,"I was stumped at first as well, but I think I understand the cause.

I believe the issue lies in [load_keyring](/kang/python-keyring-lib/src/3.0.2/keyring/core.py?at=default#cl-72). The load_module brings the modules in recursively, but not as packages - just importing the modules directly, but it only does this if the modules aren't already present in sys.modules (as their full package version).

In Keyring 2.x and earlier, all of the keyrings were imported early due to the side-effects of [this import](/kang/python-keyring-lib/src/3.0.2/keyring/core.py?at=default#cl-13). In Keyring 3, the backends are only loaded [if no keyring was specified in the config](/kang/python-keyring-lib/src/3.0.2/keyring/core.py?at=default#cl-61).

So you were right. The `__import__` in backend.py is related, but the underlying cause is a historical reliance on using that import mechanism to bypass a bug in load_keyring.

I'll try to get a fix out soon.

----------------------------------------
Original comment by: Jason R. Coombs
",{},,User,False
