1457,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-20 18:41:29+00:00,68290807,Stewori/pytypes,585279,mitar,,,352015128,414420468,"After more experimentation with this, I think it is OK as it is. I didn't see that installed hook calls into the original `excepthook` if it is disabled. It is a bit ugly that `excepthook` is modified, but I think such monkey patching is normal in Python.

My main reason for disabling was that sometimes Pytypes `excepthook` fails to modify the stack and throws and error. I think it should really be implemented more defensively with less assumptions about the stack. Like:

```
Error in sys.excepthook:
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/pytypes/util.py"", line 821, in _pytypes_excepthook
traceback.print_exception(exctype, value, tb, _calc_traceback_limit(tb))
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/pytypes/util.py"", line 765, in _calc_traceback_limit
if tb2.tb_next.tb_frame.f_code.co_filename.split(os.sep)[-2] == 'pytypes' and not \
IndexError: list index out of range
```",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
