1747,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-12 13:57:21+00:00,11380094,msiemens/tinydb,1873922,msiemens,,,254901002,328861140,"> I think it is unnecessarily confusing that currently the list in the initial record contains dicts which all have the same key, while the second record contains a list of values.

You're right about that! To be honest, I was too lazy to come up with a new example for the second case but you're totally right that it's actually kind of confusing. I've now reordered the examples so searching with lists comes first and then we introduce a new example for nested queries.

> db.search(Query().groups.any('user'))

BTW, this actually only works by accident. Python lets `'foo' in 'foo'` evaluate to `True`, but this doesn't work when using ints for example. So the proper way to use a query like this would still be

> db.search(Query().groups.any(['user']))

I'm not sure though whether or nor we should add a note about this special case in the docs...",{},OWNER,User,False
