1856,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-24 14:24:43+00:00,48009504,tbug/aiochannel,195468,tbug,,,150660399,213969122,"Ah, I wrapped my head around it now.
It's actually Guido's code
https://github.com/python/cpython/commit/5df8f554e9501816ca6ebe1df5bdaf8f0fdc5e2b
and it kind of makes sense. It is possible that the `get()` is cancelled from the outside, but an item is available inside, and the getter has been scheduled to wake up.

So the logic is:
- In any case, call `cancel()` on the future, which sets state to cancelled (if it is pending), otherwise does nothing.
- if the queue is not empty, and the getter is not in a cancelled state (this is the edge case described above) schedule a wake up for the next getter, and raise whatever exception was thrown.",{},,User,False
1857,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-19 09:57:48+00:00,20236160,thebjorn/pydeps,1193143,thebjorn,,,283162057,352695082,"Does it help if you think of the nodes as sources and sinks?  I've gotten pretty used to reading top -> down as general to specific, but I'm open to a PR that introduces a flag (e.g. `--reverse`) that reverses the dependency indicators. Because of the way graphivz works (digraph arrows go down, or to the right) it would mean that the graph would be ""upside down"".",{},OWNER,User,False
