2559,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-09 22:13:32+00:00,9590543,josiahcarlson/rom,14239698,healiseu,,,348918198,411914899,"I fully understand that trying to cover many generic query cases in ROM and at the same time maintaining a simple to use command line interface is not an easy task. Sorting and filtering are distinct operations and have to be treated separately so that they can be combined. But although this is true for the API logic, behind the scenes a memory/speed optimization can dictate a different approach....",{},NONE,User,False
2564,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-24 22:13:18+00:00,41279279,jsvine/pdfplumber,534702,jsvine,,,123825006,167162943,"Thanks, Jacob! Nice opportunity to explain some of the thinking behind pdfplumber.

> This is more of a question than an issue: do you plan to make PDFMiner's LTTextLine and LTTextBox objects / hierarchy available through pdfplumber?

The earliest prototypes for pdfplumber did, in fact, provide access to `LTTextLine` and `LTTextBox`, but I ended up ditching them, for a few reasons:

1. I found that, when it came to extracting structured data (rather than, say, plain ol' lines of text), the results of the  `LTTextLine` and `LTTextBox` algorithms almost never returned what I needed. It'd seem promising at first, but then I'd end up having to reconstruct everything from the raw chars, lines, and rects. 

2.  `LTTextLine` and `LTTextBox` are already available through PDFMiner's `pdf2txt` utility, with the `-t xml` flag.

3. Removing PDFMiner's layout analysis routines speeds things up slightly.

> Or is the point of this to make only the raw character positions available so that one can roll one's own layout analysis without PDFMiner getting in the way at all?

Yep, that's pretty much it!

All that said, I'm open to being persuaded otherwise. What do you think?",{},,User,False
