2776,IssueCommentEvent,2015-01-10 06:18:20+00:00,29014682,rocky/pycolumnize,8851,rocky,,,53946696,69445245,"It's not about Python3 per se, but a change in the view of the Python committee that has made it harder to use main code in modules. This has been in conjunction with the change to go from easy_install to pip and various loader changes over time. 

The Python3 aspect was just the _reason_ I think that Mark felt compelled to revise his book. 

The thing that has kind of always pissed me off about Python in general is many/most other language swill do something in one way, and user ask for the feature over and over again and then Python goes off and does it in another way for not a suitably good reason. 

Take backtick for example. This was originally in POSIX shell. Perl adopted it, then so did Ruby. Python doesn't and only very very late in the game was the subprocess module added. 

Variable interpolation, same thing. It was in POSIX shell, then Perl, then Ruby (but probably other languages as well). Python originally no. Then when people clamor for it enough, it gets added in a slightly different way that isn't sufficiently better to justify its being different. ",{},,User,False
