2971,IssueCommentEvent,2015-01-18 06:49:16+00:00,2725322,erikrose/blessings,295816,erikrose,,,54651042,70398538,"> great lengths were made to allow programs to be piped to less(1) which may use keyboard input

I gave this some thought. I think there are limits to how much pipeability we can accomplish automatically. I always said that one should examine vars like `does_styling` and explicitly decide, based thereon, whether to draw—well—""frippery"" was the word I used. Now, in most cases, we could return '' as if the call to key() timed out. However, if somebody calls the block-forever variant key(0), we're out of luck. Can you think of any way to make it behave on a no-input Terminal that won't confuse and surprise the caller, which had quite reasonably assumed some input? I could hear arguments for key(>0) quietly returning '', but I'm honestly having trouble coming up with a scenario in which piping an interactive program makes sense in principle. Perhaps there might be some batch job that would churn happily along if unmolested, but if you pressed P it would pause.

After typing the above, I could see making key(>0) quietly return '' and key(0) raise NoKeyboard. How does that strike you? (I may change my mind again halfway through implementing; I'm inventing rather than extracting here, always a dangerous proposition. So please do inform my musings with concrete usage scenarios from your BBS.)",{},,User,False
