3107,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-25 13:51:15+00:00,59235,mkleehammer/pyodbc,40787601,logicalextreme,,,344403654,407761137,"It looks like `None` being the first value for a column triggers all text for that column to be encoded as UTF-16LE — which is fine if the column's an `nvarchar` or `nchar` (SQLWCHAR) but isn't a supported encoding for `varchar` or `char` (SQLCHAR), as noted [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/odbc/linux-mac/programming-guidelines?view=sql-server-2017#character-set-support).

As with #371 you can explicitly encode strings as `utf8` but this adds overhead that you don't want when you're trying to take advantage of `fast_executemany`.

",{},NONE,User,False
