3292,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-02 21:19:36+00:00,65155092,ClimbsRocks/auto_ml,7017045,ClimbsRocks,,,270600715,341561467,"ugh, that's the kind of error i hate. 

it's some weird combination of windows, python version, parallelism, and pickling/pathos. 

i'm probably not going to be a ton of help fixing this one, because it's pretty environment specific. i'm gonna give the answer i hate of ""it works in our test suite and in all the environments i can run it in"", but that doesn't help you, because you're on windows and probably can't just switch over to a linux environment. 

i'll tell you what i can:

- the issue is caused when we go to pickle either a function or a method before creating a new process to run it in. this is part of how sklearn parallelizes GridSearchCV
- if you feel like modifying the source code to try things out, you can comment out some lines at the start of `predictor.py` that deal with copy_reg: lines 54 - 65 here https://github.com/ClimbsRocks/auto_ml/blob/master/auto_ml/predictor.py#L54
- you might be able to solve the issue by switching to a different version of python
- you almost certainly will be able to solve the issue by switching to a unix environment (that's what our test suite uses. we have a test for this in our test suite, and it passes)


or, you can sidestep the issue entirely, and just train up individual predictors and compare them manually. this is obviously inelegant and not the ideal solution. but, you can easily change model names with `ml_predictor.train(data, model_names='GradientBoostingClassifer')` and changing it to something like `ml_predictor.train(data, model_names='RandomForestClassifier')`

i'm really sorry i'm not more help. i think the modifying source code approach might work. if you do, try cloning down this project to whatever director you're doing ML in, and then in your script before you have `from auto_ml import Predictor` put something like
```
import os
import sys
sys.path.insert(0, os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'auto_ml'))
```
and that will import your local copy of auto_ml. you'll probably also have to `pip uninstall auto_ml` from your env, so it doesn't get confused. 

if you do solve this, please let me know! i don't have any windows boxes to dev on, so i'm always hungry to learn what i can do to make this more cross-platform compatible. 

thanks for filing the bug! hope it's an easy one to resolve. ",{},OWNER,User,False
3301,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-26 18:00:36+00:00,65155092,ClimbsRocks/auto_ml,7017045,ClimbsRocks,,,260657641,332283388,"ugh, data type issues. our transformation pipeline tries to use scipy.sparse matrices by default (more memory efficient, obviously), but makes datasets dense if it has to. sklearn was weird about what datasets you could use with gradientboosting (you could train on sparse, but not predict on sparse, if i recall). i thought i'd handled all of those edge cases, and had been using this functionality myself for a while, so i'm a bit surprised to see it rearing it's ugly head again. 

thanks for filing the issue! would love to hear anything else you encounter as you work with auto_ml more, or any ideas you have. and of course, pull requests (particularly on documentation) are super welcomed! ",{},OWNER,User,False
