3318,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-02 14:30:02+00:00,39159799,JoelBender/bacpypes,10273490,JoelBender,,,319349177,385997598,"You are correct, without the ability to be in the same ""broadcast domain"" as the other devices your Who-Is  broadcast request won't go where you want it to go.  There are two solutions, (1) install a BBMD on the network where the router is located (and there might already be one there) and become a foreign device that registers with the BBMD or (2) use ""static"" routes.

Starting with (1) assume that there is a BBMD already install on the network.  You can run the `DeviceDiscoveryForeign.py` application which uses a subtly different BACnet/IP Virtual Link Layer (BVLL) which needs the IP address of the BBMD and a time-to-live to maintain the registration.  Your broadcast Who-Is is sent to the BBMD which broadcasts it on your behalf.  The router-to-network traffic is forwarded as well, so the I-Am response comes back as you might expect.

With option (2) there is an additional command in the `ReadProperty.py` called `rtn` and it is used to tell the network layer of your application the address to use for your network 200.  Once the route is established by telling the network layer of your application (the Network Service Access Point) it won't need to do any broadcasts.

There is a *very* remote chance that your network uses IPv4 Class D multicast address *and* your VPN service will span the multicast group across the VPN.  In this *very rare* case, your broadcasts will be forwarded for you by the VPN/router and you don't need to do anything.  There is a better chance this will become more widespread with IPv6.",{},OWNER,User,False
