4551,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-30 17:07:31+00:00,58094079,orbingol/NURBS-Python,32395687,Nodli,,,345540893,408938157,"I did some research on this today and it seems you were right.

Details about what i am saying are in this paper ""Evaluation and properties of the derivative of a NURBS Curve"", S. Floater (https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/23cf/5b46ea38dd321c525bf952bde459dbf1be33.pdf).

The equation from the book comes from the ""hodograph formula"" for non-rational Bezier and BSplines (Eq (5) p.6 in the paper) by identifying the evaluation formula in this one.
However when adapting the hodograph formula for rational curves(Eq (14) p.8), either Bezier or BSplines, more terms are related to the basis functions and their derivatives and I don't think it is possible to identify the evaluation formula.

Unfortunately I could not find any other method for rational curves...

",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
4552,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-19 21:52:10+00:00,58094079,orbingol/NURBS-Python,5276943,orbingol,,,227732497,309584217,"@nortikin I would answer your first question as yes, but no :)

Well, actually it is impossible to underestimate the advantages of numpy package in programming mathematical tools, but I believe that people use numpy a lot even it is unnecessary to use in some development environments. It would be very advantageous to use numpy in this NURBS package, but I believe that if I could do it with minimum dependencies, I should do it like that.

However, I think you might want to ask for a feature which returns a numpy array instead of a 2D native list structure. That is something doable but it should be optional, so that people who are not using numpy package can use this NURBS package too. Not everyone is using the well-known Python distributions (including me) and in some development environments, it might be impossible to install/compile some of the dependencies (I have seen some).

I am very open to developing new features that people can advantage of. If you could open **a new feature request** with all possible details (and with some reasons on why we should add it to this package), I would try to implement as soon as possible.",{},,User,False
