4623,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-23 08:11:40+00:00,58694159,timdaman/check_docker,164636,KristianLyng,,,178618379,249129981,"Your idea makes some sense, but wasn't what I originally thought of.

Basically, if a service restarts, I want an alert. There are two ways of doing this: watch for the actual event, or check if uptime is lower than some interval. 

This is basically the shell script implementation (minus return codes and actual sanity):
```
kly@leia:~$ docker inspect gondul-db-test | sed 's/["",]//g' | awk 'BEGIN { ""date +%s"" | getline real } /StartedAt/ { ""date +%s --date "" $2 | getline start;}  END { uptime=(real - start); if (uptime < 600) printf ""CRITICAL: ""; else if (uptime < 1800) printf ""WARNING: ""; else printf ""OK: ""; printf ""Uptime: %s seconds\n"", uptime;}' 
CRITICAL: Uptime: 535 seconds
kly@leia:~$ docker ps
CONTAINER ID        IMAGE               COMMAND                  CREATED             STATUS              PORTS               NAMES
8aa3bb0bd9ce        gondul-db-test      ""/bin/sh -c 'pg_ctlcl""   12 days ago         Up 9 minutes        5432/tcp            gondul-db-test
```",{},,User,False
