5053,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-08 12:37:50+00:00,36964309,jantman/awslimitchecker,273454,jantman,,,132048135,181350621,"@rohawamr how did you get those parameters? That looks to me like the [STS](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/STS/latest/APIReference/Welcome.html) [Credentials response type](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/STS/latest/APIReference/API_Credentials.html), i.e. what you'd get back from a [GetSessionToken](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/STS/latest/APIReference/API_GetSessionToken.html) or maybe [GetFederationToken](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/STS/latest/APIReference/API_GetFederationToken.html) call. If that's the case, there are a few problems:

1. These are temporary credentials, so they'll have a limited lifetime (the default is 12 hours, and the maximum is 36 hours).
2. Right now, ``awslimitchecker`` doesn't have a way to pass in session credentials.

One option would be to just try without the session token, if they're not really session credentials:

```bash
export HISTCONTROL=ignorespace
 export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=<value of aws_access_key_id>
 export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=<value of aws_secret_access_key>
awslimitchecker -r <region>
```

There are two main assumptions which led to ``awslimitchecker`` not having the ability to authenticate with session credentials:

1. The assumption that ``awslimitchecker`` will be used by people with administrative access to the account.
2. The assumption that ``awslimitchecker`` will usually be run by some automated tool (i.e. a ``cron`` job or something like Jenkins or Rundeck), and therefore that limited-lifetime credentials will not be useful.

Assuming the above code doesn't work and these are, in fact, session or federation credentials, I believe that I can add support for this but it would take a few days.",{},,User,False
