5712,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-06 23:32:36+00:00,34016445,peterbrittain/asciimatics,10300669,aalireza,,,233884392,306644065,"The reason for not modifying the `CheckBox` is that `CheckBox` returns a Boolean irrespective of the value's symbols e.g. If `✓` is a symbol for `True`, `True` is returned whereas `MultiCheckBox` returns the symbols themselves [1]. Having a class behave completely differently based on a given keyword is kind of pathological.

I could avoid overriding `update` and `process` event [2], but in hindsight this `MultiCheckBox` is kind of a niche. I'll add symbol-independent tri-states by modifying `CheckBox` in a new pull request.



[1]: The reason is that the easiest way to get something that truly behaves like `True`, `False` or `None` is to modify `ast.NameConstant` prior to running the the program which is just too much and not really compatible with older versions. A hackish-way could have worked by defining something like a `quote`, but not all objects in python have a fixed `__name__` attribute.

[2]: I could have a mapping from symbols to values and use that mapping in line [1659](https://github.com/peterbrittain/asciimatics/pull/73/files#diff-6a1309fda94288cbcca002d635c86f0eR1659) (and its inverse in line [1672](https://github.com/peterbrittain/asciimatics/pull/73/files#diff-6a1309fda94288cbcca002d635c86f0eR1672)) and then override those instead of `process_event` and `update`.",{},,User,False
