6828,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-30 08:53:16+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,22437510,TaoLv,47359,apache,291315654,361519560,"Hi Chris, thanks for your detailed explaination for the omp threads in operator. I used vtune to see the running state of all omp threads in a mxnet workload. I just list my observation here for your information to see if them make sense. I found that 112 omp worker threads were created on my machine (skylake with 56 cores on 2 socket, `OMP_NUM_THREADS` is set to 56). It seems the first 56 threads were created for operator tuning and went into idle after finishing the tuning task. The last 56 threads were created for operator computation. After set `USE_OPERATOR_TUNING=0` and rebuilt mxnet, the first 56 threads were not there anymore. Do you think this behaviour is as expectaton?
Regarding to the omp threads in operator, to my understanding, if there is no operator parallelism, maybe we should give as many threads as possible to the running operator, especially for mkldnn operator. Yes, operator parallelism is totally another topic. In that case, framework should decied how many threads should be given to each operator, so they can be well overlaped.
I think, for mordern deep learning workloads and stencil computation, it would be better to keep a worker thread pool and bind one worker thread to one dedicated core. So the number of worker threads may be same with the number of physical cores on machine. If there are a lot of IO tasks in the workload, maybe we need remain several threads and cores for that. Anyway, thread binding will remove the overhead of thread switching and improve the cache efficiency for dense computation. 

FYI, I use below cmd to set thread affinity and thread number on my machine.
```
export KMP_AFFINITY=granularity=fine,noduplicates,compact,1,0
export OMP_NUM_THREADS=56
```",{},NONE,User,False
