7391,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-18 13:43:40+00:00,11015349,dimagi/jsonobject,137212,dannyroberts,94514,dimagi,141729288,198366405,"@KeithTsui thanks for the contribution. I think both of these changes have real merit, and I want to help get them in, but it's going to require a bit more than the basic implementation you've done here. As @czue noted, this library is heavily tested on exact inputs and outputs, and the changes you're suggesting are pretty far reaching. We aim heavily to be backwards compatible `couchdbkit` as well as previous versions of this library (`jsonobject`).

For both of your changes, I think there are good ways to make them backwards compatible.

For (2), I would add an additional argument called `exclude_if_is_none` that has the behavior you are looking for. Now, that's pretty confusing and you're right that `exclude_if_none` was a poor choice of words. So I'd add a deprecation warning if that param is set to `True`, letting the person writing the client code to use `exclude_if_falsey` instead. Both `exclude_if_none` and `exclude_if_falsey` will live side-by-side and do the same thing, but `exclude_if_none` will have a deprecation warning and `exclude_if_falsey` will be preferred. Then, if you want your behavior you can write:

```python
BooleanProperty(exclude_if_is_none=True)
```

current code using `exclude_if_none` will continue to work (with a deprecation warning), and new code that wants that behavior can use

```python
BooleanProperty(exclude_if_falsey=True)
```

That's for (2). For (1) I suggest having someone who wants to override the default explicitly declare that at the beginning of their code. So that would look like:

```python
import jsonobject
jsonobject.configure_defaults(exclude_if_is_none=True)
```

This would have to be called before any `jsonobject.JsonObject` classes were declared.

Then inside `JsonProperty.__init__`, you could have `exclude_if_is_none=None` in the params and then have something like

```python
if exclude_if_is_none is None:
    exclude_if_is_none = get_default_configuration().exclude_if_is_none
```

Currently, neither `get_default_configuration` nor `configure_defaults` exist, so that would have to be part of the change. Since there are plenty of default behaviors that one might want to configure, having that infrastructure in this library will make it accessible to a wider audience and I think would overall be a very healthy thing.

Please, feel free to reach out for more information. If you're interested in taking on this larger task, I'd be happy to spend the time to make sure you're able to do it well and answer questions you might have along the way.",{},,User,False
7396,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-15 09:30:14+00:00,788264,zeromq/pyzmq,7189309,lab313ru,109777,zeromq,228559538,301424212,"Not yet publicly available, but I'll make it for you.

For now you may test such situation:
C side: Two pair sockets, different ports, the same context
Python side: Two pair sockets, the same ports as in C part, the same context.

One C socket waits for input messages, and other socket sends requests to the Python side, and waits for response. Both in different threads.

At the Python part the second socket waits for input messages, and depending on received data, responses to the first or to the second socket. One thread is used here.",{},,User,False
7397,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-30 11:16:33+00:00,788264,zeromq/pyzmq,151929,minrk,109777,zeromq,314057142,385370121,"This is a bug. An elusive one. The root cause of this is that a context has its `.term()` called during `__del__` before one or more of its sockets is closed. This will hang until the context is closed.

Closing sockets and contexts via garbage collection during process teardown has been a tricky issue since Python 3.4 changed how that works (in particular, it deliberately increased the randomness of order of the cleanup process).

I was able to reproduce this, and it turned out the `__dealloc__` is being called (which doesn't call `.close()`), but `__del__` is not (which does call close). So the fix should be #1173, which ensures that close is called in `__dealloc__` if it hasn't already been called by `__del__`.

The simplest workaround in the meantime is to call `ctx.destroy()` at the end of your script, which closes all sockets in order and terminates the context.",{},OWNER,User,False
7400,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-24 12:47:18+00:00,788264,zeromq/pyzmq,1276956,dimpase,109777,zeromq,26806382,262768795,"@minrk it's pyzmq 16.0.0.

It looks like that because of distutils(?) picking wrong `cc` for some reason (I guess, like ""we're on Linux! gcc!"") it sets `rpath` wrongly. Strangely `pyzmq` is the only Python package (out of quite a few, as you know) in Sage that fails to build with this setup.

One sets environment variables CC=clang and CXX=clang++, and expect setup/distutils to take notice.
This seems not to be the case here.
",{},,User,False
7401,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-21 16:08:11+00:00,788264,zeromq/pyzmq,151929,minrk,109777,zeromq,196273893,268561429,"Thanks for the test case!

> What you are saying is that Test Case 1a should be FAIL

Yes, I would consider that a failure to do the intended/expected action. It's not hypothetical, either; it's something that I rely upon on a regular basis. It is important that users be able to prevent SIGINT to the parent from halting the child, ideally in the simple, standard way that works for all subprocesses spawned from Python. Taking away valid user choices is something I prefer to avoid.

This PR does reduce the negative consequences of certain non-default choices (i.e. registering signal handlers without including proper cleanup code in the parent), but it makes important, valid use cases unavailable.",{},,User,False
