7765,IssueCommentEvent,2015-03-09 01:35:58+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,10010231,landscape-bot,251374,spotify,60285711,77788206,"[![Code Health](https://landscape.io/badge/122261/landscape.svg?style=flat)](https://landscape.io/diff/107800)
Code quality remained the same when pulling **[afa299b](https://github.com/spotify/luigi/commit/afa299bb60fd75437aecb15c0e42285b0bc46ac9) on spotify:erikbern/fix-822-2** into **[67912ab](https://github.com/spotify/luigi/commit/67912aba66c2e890b5f524832853ac4f7758f36c) on spotify:master**.",{},,User,False
7766,IssueCommentEvent,2015-09-14 16:43:47+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,1027979,erikbern,251374,spotify,106369692,140140641,"https://github.com/spotify/luigi/blob/master/luigi/worker.py#L104

It's a bit tricky. The idea with `to_str_params` and `from_str_params` is that the type is defined by the parameter class (i.e. `IntParameter` etc). But `None` is not the same type as the parameter. You would see the same error if you passed a string to an `IntParameter` etc.

Not sure how to solve. Probably the only way to solve it is to avoid using `to_str_params` and `from_str_params` and use some other serialization mechanism. Alternatively I wonder if we should just enforce type adherence and actually throw an error if types are not matching (eg `to_str_params` would only serialize strings and nothing else)",{},,User,False
