8788,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-17 18:37:14+00:00,34527721,scrapy/parsel,37565,eliasdorneles,733635,scrapy,100686360,131920190,"Just to make my point clear, I agree we can add custom xpath functions, I just mean we should be careful about it.

I guess I'm looking for a set of best practices for these functions, or rather, a set of good examples.

I agree that `has-class` is a good candidate, but I think we have to figure out proper ways for error handling in case of misuse.

Examples of misuse (using latest parsel and registering the has_class function from the example above):

```
>>> from parsel import Selector
>>> import mycustomxpaths
>>> import requests
>>> sel = Selector(text=requests.get('http://stackoverflow.com').text)
>>> sel.xpath('//div[has-class(//body)]') # this fails silently
[]
>>> sel.xpath('//div[has-class()]') # this renders a weird error
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ValueError                                Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-12-ebb52fb24d69> in <module>()
----> 1 sel.xpath('//div[has-class()]') # this renders a weird error

/home/elias/hacking/scrapinghub/parsel/parsel/selector.pyc in xpath(self, query)
    130         except etree.XPathError:
    131             msg = u""Invalid XPath: %s"" % query
--> 132             raise ValueError(msg if six.PY3 else msg.encode(""unicode_escape""))
    133 
    134         if type(result) is not list:

ValueError: Invalid XPath: //div[has-class()]
>>> sel.xpath('//div[has-class(has-class())]') # and this segfaults
Segmentation fault
```

I think we can put some checks in place for the first two cases, but I don't know how to handle the last one (or even if we should try to).

This is mainly why I'm not in a hurry to add these functions, but I do agree that it would be nice to have them (perhaps after 1.0). But maybe I'm being too conservative? =)",{},,User,False
