8981,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-28 03:30:41+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,2184487,JDWarner,897180,scikit-image,170332668,250062938,"Look again, @jni - this is an excellent and compelling example.  The goal isn't maximizing the amount of noise removed, it's addressing the color accuracy problems introduced by denoising.  

When you denoise, you need to tailor your methods to your noise. The way this example is structured, we add a lot of chroma noise.  In other words, the noise is random and uncorrelated between channels, That gives you the color mishmash shown in the raw noisy image.  Another example might deal exclusively with luminance noise, but that's out of the scope of this PR.

YCbCr is true to the original image's color despite this, even when truly random chroma noise is added, and that's the point of the example.  RGB denoising, when turned up high enough, can sort of smear this over at the expense of details - but color accuracy always suffers.  You never gets as good as YCbCr.  Look at them both at 100-200%, comparing the out-of-focus bokeh areas, and you'll see this.  

Because it's better suited to this noise, YCbCr is also preserving more detail at the same denoising strength.  If you naively think the best result will be the smoothest, RGB might at first glance appear ahead - but it isn't. 

@soupault - Context managers for this kind of thing quickly lead toward pipeline workflows.  VTK and similar use these, and they have benefits, but that philosophy is not at all easily integrated into scikit-image given the choices we've made to date.  We could discuss how that would look, but it's out of scope for this PR.  Feel free to raise that as a separate Issue (or Project) for consideration, but let's keep this narrowly focused on the example.

Finally, as far as my review is concerned:  There are a few minor test suite complaints which should be simple to address.",{},,User,False
