10358,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-23 09:43:27+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,3407345,CyberDem0n,1564818,zalando,248969973,346570616,"> It runs well using an emptyDir but switching the a persistent volume (which is commented out in (patroni_k8s.yaml) gives me a permissions issue. 

If you are using docker image build from this branch - it will likely not work with persistent volumes.
Container starts with unprivileged postgres user and can't write into a persistent volume.

Helm chart is using a [spilo](https://github.com/zalando/spilo/tree/master/postgres-appliance) image, which starts as root and changes ownership of PGROOT before starting patroni and bunch of other stuff: https://github.com/zalando/spilo/blob/master/postgres-appliance/launch.sh#L6

Actually I've already did some changes to spilo: https://github.com/zalando/spilo/pull/198 to support kubernetes branch, postgres-10 and to make it much smaller. Latest image is: registry.opensource.zalan.do/acid/spilo-10:1.3-p4
You can try to build it on your own, but before that you have to install docker-squash: 
```bash
$ sudo pip install docker-squash
$ ./build.sh --build-arg DEMO=true --build-arg COMPRESS=true -t spilo .
```

Spilo solves a lot of configuration problems for you. It will create the right patroni.yaml with proper kubernetes settings: https://github.com/zalando/spilo/pull/198/files#diff-9ec119124414a288bc2f1edd468dcce5R330

Also it actually prefers to use kubernetes endpoints for leader elections instead of config maps.


> I played a bit with labels and am not quite sure now the env var PATRONI_KUBERNETES_LABELS is used. It seems I'm not completely free in choosing labels. The label cluster-name seems to be required.

Labels are playing two different roles:
1. They are used to find existing objects related to your postgres cluster: (endpoints or configmaps) + pods
2. These labels will be applied to any object Patroni creates (endpoints or configmaps) in order to be able to find those objects later.

In addition to that there Patroni needs to know which label is used to keep cluster name and role.
Such names are configured via `kubernetes.scope_label` and `kubernetes.role_label`.

If `kubernetes.scope_label` is not set, Patroni will use `cluster-name` for that, but in Spilo docker image we are using `version` label: https://github.com/zalando/spilo/pull/198/files#diff-9ec119124414a288bc2f1edd468dcce5R374
If `kubernetes.role_label` is not set, Patroni will use `role` for that, but in Spilo docker we are using `spilo-role`: https://github.com/zalando/spilo/pull/198/files#diff-9ec119124414a288bc2f1edd468dcce5R373

> Since you mentioned you already run it on a few clusters: Do you publish Docker images from this branch in your registry that are publically available and could be used by the chart? I could even create a PR to already publish the chart in the charts repo so people can try it. Would that make sense at this point?

Image is published (see above), but we would really like to make it more ""official"", i.e. merge this PR, and later merge Spilo PR.",{},MEMBER,User,False
