10987,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-25 15:52:03+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,520669,dhermes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,102930119,134642166,"@jgeewax I should note that I made some changes from your original

- Got rid of `Client.get_project` (per discussion in #911). However I made it very clear in the docstrings of both `Client.project` (factory) and `Project.reload` that they needed one another to actually get data.
- Added all `Project` constructor args to the `Client.project` factory
- Used Py3 `print(project)` in docstrings
- Trimmed down many docstrings (i.e. now just one-liner docstrings on each module, most methods no longer have **example** snippets)
- Adding `august 2015` next to the parenthetical `currently`
- Made the constructors fail if service account credentials were used (also disabled the `from_service_account_*` factories for the `Client`)
- Moved `_ProjectIterator` definition to module-level in `Client` instead of defined in the method call.
- Switched the order of `client` and `name` in the `Project` constructor
- Made `_require_client` just emulate other uses (not throw a `ValueError`) since a missing client will result in `(None).connection` eventually, which is an `AttributeError` (LBYL vs. EAFP)
- Made the `reload_data` flags default to `False` instead of `True` (explained in f79c04911d617d66c5ed0a4fbc5c9a12f683a186)
- Making the dummy test `_Client` a container for `connection` and nothing else. (It previously inherited from the real `Client`, we avoid leakage between modules for tests at all costs)",{},,User,False
10989,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-08 16:07:45+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,520669,dhermes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,159202337,224640705,"It's not really about the code execution, the backend should reject the request if you really didn't have write permissions, then we'd throw an exception for a non-200 response. By default `read_write` is [one of the scopes][1] used when creating auth tokens, so if the account does have write access it will.

Maybe the writer/reader permissions on that account aren't quite what they seem?

You saying the `upload_from_string` call fails to upload and there is no indication of the failure. Have you checked after the fact that nothing got uploaded?

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/92e9362f5246ecea1a9f96ea104353d3caf7623c/gcloud/storage/connection.py#L40-L42",{},,User,False
