11632,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-18 12:36:32+00:00,30618733,prometheus/client_python,135807,ecksun,3380462,prometheus,202886203,302390951,"> We don't currently support multiprocessing, as it doesn't work the way we expect gunicorn-like things to.

> We currently support a partiuclar model of using multiple processes, not particular libraries.

There is not much documentation about what is and is not supported, nor what model you are refering to, could you expand on that @brian-brazil ?

I have a kafka multiprocess worker which I want to export metrics from. The code below appears to work (I intend to use systemd ExecStopPost to cleanup afterwards), is there something I'm missing?

```python
def start_prometheus_server():
    class MetricsHandler(BaseHTTPRequestHandler):
        def do_GET(self):
            if self.path == '/metrics':
                self.respond_metrics()
            else:
                self.respond_not_found()

        def respond_not_found(self):
            self.send_response(404)
            self.send_header('Content-Type', 'text/plain')
            self.end_headers()
            self.wfile.write(b'Use /metrics\n')

        def respond_metrics(self):
            registry = CollectorRegistry()
            multiprocess.MultiProcessCollector(registry)
            data = generate_latest(registry)
            self.send_response_only(200)
            self.send_header('Content-Type', CONTENT_TYPE_LATEST)
            self.send_header('Content-Length', str(len(data)))
            self.end_headers()
            self.wfile.write(data)

    class PrometheusMetricsServer(threading.Thread):
        def run(self):
            httpd = HTTPServer(('', 8002), MetricsHandler)
            httpd.serve_forever()

    t = PrometheusMetricsServer()
    t.daemon = True
    t.start()
```",{},,User,False
