11664,IssueCommentEvent,2015-02-27 04:41:00+00:00,13592924,python-openxml/python-docx,2062718,scanny,3403760,python-openxml,43634080,76329710,"You're going to need a bit different approach because you're working with a new row, one that doesn't yet have either a `w:trPr` or `w:trHeight` element:

```python
# these imports can go at the top of the file
from docx.oxml import OxmlElement
from docx.oxml.ns import qn

row = table.add_row()
tr = row._tr
trPr = tr.get_or_add_trPr()
trHeight = OxmlElement('w:trHeight')
trHeight.set(qn('w:val'), ""2092000"")
trHeight.set(qn('w:hRule'), ""atLeast"")
trPr.append(trHeight)
```
The `row = row.cells` line is unnecessary for this purpose.",{},,User,False
11665,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-24 06:20:40+00:00,13592924,python-openxml/python-docx,2062718,scanny,3403760,python-openxml,42985558,114744595,"Ok, well, it looks like `w:commentRangeStart` (and End) can be a child of multiple parents. Better check the XML Schema to see which ones. For your purposes, to keep it simple, you might want to make it a child of a run if you can, rather than a text (`<w:t>`) element.

Something along the lines of this aircode should get it done for you:

```python
def add_comment_start_to_run(run, id):
    r = run._r
    commentRangeStart = OxmlElement('w:commentRangeStart')
    commentRangeStart.set(qn('w:id'), str(id))
    _r.append(commentRangeStart)
```

Check the __init__() method in Run to confirm the element name. It might be _element instead of _r.

Let us know how you go :)",{},,User,False
