11697,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-15 13:58:27+00:00,9861437,imageio/imageio,1454335,kuchi,3678179,imageio,195695477,267333387,"Sorry for not being clearer. Yes, from what the FFMPEG documentation page
says, frame accurate seeking with one call to -ss should work starting in
v2.1. On my system it looks like imageio is using 2.6.3, and it works fine
with the single call in my testing. So there is no need for an update from
what you currently have.

There is one issue i've noticed that I haven't been able to track down yet.
If you play a video in reverse, after about ~200 frames it hangs on my
system (even before this pull request). So I'm not sure if there is some
issue of calling _reinitialize many times that something is going wrong.
Don't know if you have encountered this. If I get time I can try and make a
test to illustrate this failure.

One other question, what do you think about having the ability to get
frames by indexing? This might make the returned object more pythonic, as in
   mov = imageio.get_reader(""my_video.mp4"")
   frame = mov[0]     # equivalent to mov.get_data(0)
   frame = mov[1]

Then you could support:
   for frame in mov:
          pass

Would likely be an easy addition for multi image objects. What are your
thoughts?




