12549,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-21 22:56:06+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1821014,krancour,6117407,deis,111845329,150047457,"@gred7 I couldn't use your Dockerfile because the `FROM` isn't valid and the `COPY` instructions won't work since I don't have your source.

I did the best I could by putting together this trivial example that shows @bacongobbler's suggestion works.  (fwiw, `deis-router` uses that exact trick and it works there as well.)

My Dockerfile:

```
FROM alpine:3.2

RUN ln -sf /dev/stdout /my.log

ENTRYPOINT for i in $(seq 1 10); do echo $i >> /my.log; sleep 1; done
```

To run:

```
$ docker build -t log-demo .
$ docker run -it --rm log-demo
```

You will see that everything written to `/my.log` also goes to the container's `/dev/stdout`

The only other things that might explain your issue would be if the path to the symlinks doesn't match with where your apache is actually writing logs to _or_ if you actually have a platform-wide configuration issue with `dies-logspout` or `deis-logger`-- that, however, would be immediately evident because no logs from _any_ application or platform component would show up in your Papertrail at all.",{},,User,False
