12757,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-09 19:35:53+00:00,8566509,delph-in/pydelphin,1428419,goodmami,6363662,delph-in,138686942,194470337,"Thanks! I tried the sentence with the latest SVN version of the ERG and got the parse you have; strangely the regular demo site (http://erg.delph-in.net/) doesn't get any parses.

And I initially followed the Copestake 2009 (""Slacker Semantics"") paper for finding heads. I also understand that there can be more than one head (the pyDelphin `Xmrs.labelset_heads()` function returns a list), but I think that not all heads are created equal (it's a sorted list, sorted using the heuristics described in #57), and the most ""heady"" one is selected as the target of the link. If there are multiple heads, the others get `/EQ` links with the headiest head. I use nodeid to approximate the surface order just as a last-case criterion for sorting heads. The LKB does the essentially the same thing (see `make-dmrs-eq-links` in lkb/src/rmrs/dmrs.lisp) with a comment that it should use CFROM eventually.

The code for EDS has more fine-grained head-finding criteria then either the LKB or pyDelphin (see `ed-select-representative` in lkb/src/mrs/dependencies.lisp). If I can't get pyDelphin to consistently give the appropriate link targets, I might try to more closely imitate either the DMRS or EDS methods from the LKB.",{},,User,False
