Also, please attach debug logs with `blacklist: []`, as I might be able to see some of the calls to Elasticsearch that way.  It seems to me that there's something else going on here, since I cannot replicate it with Elasticsearch 2.3.3 and Curator 4.0.3.",{},,User,False
13040,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-19 08:30:02+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,112638,faxm0dem,6764390,elastic,101834424,132491896,"curator, version 3.2.3",{},,User,False
13046,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-12 18:24:01+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,34332880,183439666,"@amulyas Well, that's why Elastic has the Shield security product.  Proxies are not very effective, though they are better than nothing.

There may be other ways to capture the version information, but this is the easiest.  If you can find another that doesn't break other functionality (or cause dramatic slowdowns), I could be persuaded to merge it.",{},,User,False
13053,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-01 13:18:57+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,32132,HonzaKral,6764390,elastic,65196294,88477637,"It definitely *must* be outside of the for loop, ideally completely outside of your code somewhere where a single instance is being created and then used throughout the code. Not only will it consume much less memory but also will be much faster since it will have only one connection open and keep reusing it.

I will look into the code in more detail to try and figure out what's going wrong.",{},,User,False
13055,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-14 16:48:55+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,146550,fxdgear,6764390,elastic,350251397,412939736,"Ouch. I'm sorry you're having issues. This is unfortunate. 

So going thorugh setup or requirements etc. won't fix the problem for you cause you are in an environment with no network connection. 

You have installed a VERY VERY old version of the client. 1.9.0. 

My recommendation would be to go to PyPI and download a tar of the version you want using the computer you're using now (to write this issue since I know you can connect to the internet with it).  Then somehow you can copy the tar file to your server. 

Depending on the version of Elasticsearch you're using you should pick the version below that most closely matches:
* [elasticsearch 6.x](https://pypi.org/project/elasticsearch/#files)
* [elasticsearch 5.x](https://pypi.org/project/elasticsearch5/#files)
* [elasticsearch 2.x](https://pypi.org/project/elasticsearch2/#files)
* [elasticsearch 1.x](https://pypi.org/project/elasticsearch1/#files)",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
13059,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-27 20:29:04+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,32132,HonzaKral,6764390,elastic,116648981,167439807,"Closing this issue since it's not really about the python client, but a more generic ES questions. I recommend using http://discuss.elastic.co/ for those.

Thanks!",{},,User,False
13061,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-11 13:11:40+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,32132,HonzaKral,6764390,elastic,227920998,300784545,"You are explicitly silencing errors when saying `ignore=400`, in that case we cannot guarantee proper behavior. If you remove that call you will get an exception informing you about what's going wrong.

