13072,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-05 15:37:32+00:00,64148806,Azure/blobxfer,7535975,alfpark,6844498,Azure,180837627,251711738,"@leovin I'm surprised that it would take that long for 10k files with MD5 disabled. One thing you can do is invoke blobxfer in parallel and either: (1) split your folder into multiple folders (either by hand or volume mounting them with docker) and use multiple blobxfer sessions in parallel, (2) pre-archive your folder into one or more archives - this will, in general be much faster, especially for Azure files (if that is what you're using), (3) use the `--include` parameter to partition off different parts of the folder and use multiple blobxfer sessions in parallel.

There are some fundamental design issues at play here that contribute to the overall potential slowness in start up and memory usage in the script. There are plans for a v2, but this is far in the future. Please let me know if the above workarounds accelerate your start up. Also please bear in mind that Azure files is not intended to be high performance.",{},,User,False
