13349,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-03 14:57:38+00:00,25611422,openaddresses/machine,382136,NelsonMinar,6895392,openaddresses,84387044,108470163,"I think the best solution is to add the `timeout` parameter to the subprocess call. That option was added in Python 3.3 and was backported to Py2: see [subprocess32](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/subprocess32/). This will make the parent process responsible for the timeout, which seems best.

Another way would be to add the [timeout decorator from the batch runner](https://github.com/openaddresses/machine/blob/master/openaddr/jobs.py#L50-L76) inside the `openaddr-process-one` program. But that doesn't feel quite right to me; it's relying on the child job to time itself out.

A third way would be to add more code to the parent launcher to implement a timeout there. I think that ends up being functionally equivalent to just using the new stuff in subprocess.

Much discussion in [this StackExchange thread](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1191374/subprocess-with-timeout). Some of the top voted answers are wrong. I'm proposing [this answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/12698328/144170).",{},,User,False
