13483,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-31 16:11:18+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,973454,arthurdarcet,7049303,aio-libs,218365204,290756835,"The test server I mentioned earlier, which used 400MB of RAM to handle a 200MB-request, was a complete aiohttp server and the request were sent using curl from the outside, through the network stack of my machine (albeit through the lo interface)


I understand the need for speed at all cost, but I still think some memory is copied unnecessarily here, with performance hits on memory mostly but probably also on time.
This `BytesIO` version is indeed slower ; I think the main issue is the double ""append to list, return b''.join(parts)"" done by read: first done here https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/streams.py#L291 but this merges parts that come from here https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/streams.py#L372 and the body is then three time in memory (original blobs, _read_no_wait version, and the result of read)
I'll update the PR to fix only this.

```
python -m timeit -s ""buffer = [b'0' * 1500] * $N"" ""res = []; [res.append(p) for p in buffer]; b''.join(res)""
python -m timeit -s ""buffer = [b'0' * 1500] * $N; import io"" ""buf = io.BytesIO(); [buf.write(p) for p in buffer]; buf.getvalue()""
```

```
- N=1
  join: 0.58 usec per loop
  BytesIO: 0.954 usec per loop

- N=10
  join: 2.25 usec per loop
  BytesIO: 4.31 usec per loop

- N=100
  join: 29.1 usec per loop
  BytesIO: 98.8 usec per loop

- N=1000
  join: 220 usec per loop
  BytesIO: 934 usec per loop
```",{},,User,False
