13923,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-29 17:21:10+00:00,27082457,HIPS/autograd,1458824,mattjj,7935606,HIPS,185660682,257103998,"Great to hear from you guys!

That's definitely a much bigger slowdown than we would like. Ken's suggestions are good ones. A general principle to keep in mind is that autograd works at the level of numpy/scipy functions as primitives, and that means the same performance rule of thumb to ""do as much as possible in terms of numpy calls"" is even more important for autograd code, since Python overheads can get amplified with autograd on both forward and backward passes while numpy calls stay cheap. That happens because autograd is tracing how primitive (numpy) operations are getting composed, then acting kind of like an interpreter (implemented in Python) on those traced operations during the reverse pass.

It could be that numpy and scipy don't provide the right primitives. In that case it can be helpful to define your own primitives and, as Ken suggests, define their gradients (ideally in terms of other primitives, so that you can get higher-order differentiation if you need it). If you can define part or all of your inner loop body as a new primitive, you don't have to lose autograd magic, and it could be much faster because it would eliminate a lot of the overhead that autograd is probably amplifying by tracing all the steps of all the iterations of that loop body, even if your primitive and its gradient are written entirely in Python.

To get the absolute best performance, you could push individual primitives down into Cython; I've been writing some [snippets to do that with variants of scipy.linalg funcions](https://github.com/mattjj/autograd_linalg). However, since your forward pass is relatively fast, I think the thing to tackle first is reducing autograd overhead. Defining your loop body as a primitive and defining its gradient could be the most direct path to doing that, and you can always further optimize by pushing things into Cython afterwards if you need to.

Your code might end up looking something like this:

```python
from autograd.core import primitive

# [...]

def calc_vector_for_single_doc(topics_KU):
    ct_topics_KU = topics_KU * word_ct_d_U[np.newaxis, :]
    K = topics_KU.shape[0]
    pi_d_K = np.ones(K) / float(K)
    # Start loop over iterations
    giter = 0
    while giter < max_iters:
        giter = giter + 1
        pi_d_K = update_pi(pi_d_K, ct_topics_KU, topics_KU)
    return pi_d_K

@primitive
def update_pi(pi_d_K, ct_topics_KU, topics_KU):
    denom_U = 1.0 / np.dot(pi_d_K, topics_KU)
    grad_K = pi_step_size * np.dot(ct_topics_KU, denom_U)
    pi_d_K = pi_d_K * np.exp(grad_K)
    pi_d_K_sum = np.sum(pi_d_K)
    return pi_d_K / pi_d_K_sum

update_pi.defgrad(lambda updated_pi_d_K, pi_d_K, ct_topics_KU, topics_KU:
                  lambda g: ...,  # TODO my cool Jacobian-transpose operation
                  argnum=0)
```

Where `g` is what we tend to call the 'outgrad', which is ∂ loss / ∂ updated_pi_d_K. One important thing to figure out is whether you'd need to define gradients with respect to the other arguments, `ct_topics_KU` and `topics_KU`. You can determine that by testing if those variables in your current code come in as boxed autograd `Node` types.

Here are some orthogonal thoughts. It looks like your inner loop is a fixed-stepsize steepest ascent optimization. Do you think it typically converges, up to some reasonable numerical tolerance? If so, there are two tweaks that could help without much code. First, you could test for convergence within some tolerance and break out of the loop early (since the average number of steps required to converge may be much less than the maximum). That could avoid superfluous loop iterations, where the overhead gets amplified by autograd. Second, if you run an inner optimization to a fixed point, you may not need to propagate gradients through the optimization procedure itself; you may just need to use the optimizing value of the decision variable and apply the implicit function theorem. (We used that in Appendix A of [the SVAE paper](http://arxiv.org/abs/1603.06277), though it's probably explained better elsewhere.) If that's the case, I can say more about how to do that with autograd, but basically you use the [`getval` function](https://github.com/HIPS/autograd/issues/106) (which behaves like Theano's `consider_constant` or TensorFlow's `stop_gradient`) to unbox the values while you're computing the fixed point.",{},,User,False
