14922,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-01 07:12:40+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,7749319,aguilera51284,10334301,marshmallow-code,113925749,152801969,thanks for the reply.,{},,User,False
14923,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-01 05:50:44+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,5924712,Lanzafame,10334301,marshmallow-code,119028177,222899197,"I am not sure that I entirely understand @frol's use case but my own sent me looking for a solution similar to what @frol describes.

My use case looks like the following:
```python
class FooSchema(Schema):
    name = fields.Str(required=True)
    country = fields.Str(required=True)
    city = fields.Str(required=True)
    operator = fields.Str(required=True)
    campus = fields.Str(required=True)
    facility = fields.Str(required=True)
```

I would like to refactor the above to following:
```python
class FooSchema(Schema):
    class Meta:
        required = (""name"", ""country"", ""city"", ""operator"", ""campus"", ""facility"")
```

Just my 2 cents.",{},,User,False
14928,IssueCommentEvent,2017-02-09 18:33:13+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,10785,maximkulkin,10334301,marshmallow-code,206475591,278731003,"This is not a framework problem and yes, it is hard to implement. By the time constructor is executed, it already doesn't have reference to `tags_id` as a field. The class dictionary contains only ""tags"", ""load_tags"" and ""tags_id"". I guess you could get a warning from a some static analysis tool like pylint. But generally you should be using proper naming conventions (e.g. name your functions with a verbs, not nouns, e.g. `process_post_dump` or `normalize_tags_ids`; prefix those method names with underscore making them non-public)",{},,User,False
