15314,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-15 15:18:53+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,13275008,GuillaumeLangelier,11668813,Z3Prover,94322227,121649661,"Alright, thank you for your answers. I wouldn’t know how to have a constant exponent in smt2 for a floating point, but I guess it wouldn’t help me much anyway since you mention that fp.mul is also non-linear. I am aware it is possible to encore a fixed point number in a machine 32 bits integer but I read that bv2int and int2bv are considered uninterpreted functions so it is making this approach less useful in my case. Moreover, even if I can circumvent that, I am guessing bvmul, bvsdiv … are also non-linear which remains a problem for what I intend to do.
 
My goal (and hope) was to avoid non-linearity by transferring to a bit representation (a la CBMC) but just when needed and use the powerful SMT-solver for the rest of the formula. CBMC is transforming numbers into a bit representation and does the arithmetic calculation using circuits-like formulas. It uses a SAT-solver in the end. It is slower due to the increased number of Boolean variables and clauses, but it does find a model on some code sample containing non-linearity where an SMT encoding + z3 approach does not terminate. They say multiplication is complex also so maybe it is because they are avoiding parts of the formula that they come up with a solution.

Anyway, I guess I am going to try to attack the problem from another angle. 

Thank you again.",{},,User,False
