15385,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-10 09:37:45+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,99482403,129382041,"Looks good except that `None`s could be in all places, not only the first dimension, and should be handled correctly (see comments). And the convolution example could be made a little simpler by using `l_in_to_hid.output_shape` for `l_hid_to_hid`'s input layer. Almost good for merging now!",{},,User,False
15387,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-29 08:30:52+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,97749383,125880255,"> As i am new to it can you please help me come out of this bug?

The last line says **Cannot find command ""git""**. It means that git is not installed. The download link for Windows seems to be: https://git-scm.com/download/win. Install it and possibly adjust your path, such that `git --version` does not throw an error. Then try again.

Alternatively, install the bleeding-edge version of Lasagne as described in the [installation instructions](http://lasagne.readthedocs.org/en/latest/user/installation.html#bleeding-edge-version); it does not require git. It may be incompatible with Daniel's code, though (that's exactly why he's giving a particular git commit in his `requirements.txt`).",{},,User,False
15390,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-23 11:25:25+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,96364675,124063011,"> I think this was the reason I originally put `*args` in the `get_output_for` signature along with `**kwargs`. Although that probably wasn't a good solution anyway.

I think the extra outputs really ought to be named rather than being given a particular order. That makes it easier to read the code, and easier to make extra outputs optional (the next layer can just check whether specific names are present or not, instead of having to be told in its constructor).

> The 'side output' stuff sounds intriguing, but I'm very wary of making the more straightforward use cases more complicated. If we add support for this kind of thing, people who do not wish to use it should be able to ignore it, and should even be allowed to be completely oblivious of the existence of this feature without it causing them any trouble.

That was the idea for the side outputs -- everything would work exactly the same as before, and you'd only need to care about this stuff when you want to make use of it.

> The most appealing option to me is also to have a single 'object' that represents the output of a layer, and maybe this object could be something other than a tensor, e.g. a list of tensors or a dictionary.

Well, another option that came to my mind was using the `tag` member of the tensor to attach extra outputs. That's what `blocks` uses to annotate the graph. I'm a bit wary of changing `get_output()` and `get_output_for()` to generally work on dictionaries instead of tensors; that would be quite much of a change.

> To avoid confusing the user/removing backwards compatibility, `get_output` would just retrieve the member of the output of the final layer corresponding to the default network output.

That's something I hadn't thought of when suggesting to propagate side outputs via `get_output_for()`'s `**kwargs`, this isn't possible for `lasagne.layers.get_output()`, but there should be a way to retrieve the side outputs. Annotating the main output tensor via its `tag` member would solve both at once. We'd still need to find a way to propagate and obtain the extra output shapes.

> I think layers would need to propagate all unused inputs always, right? What if you staked a `RecurrentLayer` on top of a `DenseLayer` on top of a `RecurrentLayer` - the `DenseLayer` would need to propagate `mask` even though it didn't use it.

Umm, I think there's no reason to do this, you'd put the `DenseLayer` inside the second `RecurrentLayer` then, with a `CustomRecurrentLayer` (otherwise it would be fully-connected to all inputs of all times steps of the sequence and it wouldn't make sense to iterate over its output with the second recurrent layer anyway). I haven't thought that through, but I don't think inputs should be propagated by default, that's difficult to accomplish anyway (how do you distinguish an ""unused input"" from a ""consumed input""?).

> One question this raises is what the semantics of the output shape of a layer should be in this case. A shape tuple only makes sense if the output of a layer is a tensor. But I guess we could make Lasagne agnostic to this as well and leave it up to the individual layer implementations to decide what type of inputs they expect / accept.
> [...] what if someone suddenly comes up with a layer that returns a completely different data type, say, a string?

Interesting thought. Yes, actually it'd be quite fine for a layer to return something completely different in `get_output_for()` and `get_output_shape_for()`, this wouldn't break Lasagne at all. It's just that `get_output_for()` is completely symbolic, limiting possibilities to Theano's data types (which don't include strings).

----

Soo... one way would be changing `get_output_for()`, `get_output_shape_for()` and `get_output()` to *always* accept and return dictionaries instead of tensors. This would be clean and consistent, but it would completely break the API, requiring changes to every single Lasagne layer in existence, and it wouldn't be unobtrusive -- every user would be aware of the possibility of passing packages of tensors tied together, even if they never use it.

Another way would be to *optionally* accept and return dictionaries instead of tensors. This would be clean, consistent, and unobtrusive, but it would mean that layers that are unaware of that possibility cannot be stacked on top of layers making use of that possibility, or would need a layer in between that picks out a single output for them.

A third way would be changing `get_output_for()` and `get_output()` to pass a dictionary of side outputs attached to the main tensor's `tag` member. This would be slightly hackish, but still unobtrusive, and it would allow to stack ordinary layers on top of multiple-output layers. However, it would need a way for the extra output shapes to be propagated through `get_output_shape_for()`, and I don't see a good way for that. Using a separate method might be the cleanest solution, but very inelegant.


I think I prefer the second option. As far as I see, it wouldn't require any changes to Lasagne, we could just add layers that return dictionaries and others that can cope with it, along with a `MultiplexLayer` that can merge multiple layers into a dictionary under given names and a `DemultiplexLayer` that can pick out a single tensor and shape from a dictionary. There wouldn't be any notion of a main tensor and side tensors. The only disadvantage is that you cannot stack, say, a `DenseLayer` on top of a layer that has multiple outputs, but need a `DemultiplexLayer` in between. But this can also be seen as an advantage in terms of ""explicit is better than implicit"".

(`MultiplexLayer` and `DemultiplexLayer` could be named differently, of course, or given aliases such as `combine_into_dict` and `pick_from_dict`.)",{},,User,False
15395,IssueCommentEvent,2016-06-27 17:53:26+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,147829555,228822524,"> The current interface hides these debug tools from the user

I don't see how. You can always do:
```python
layer = InputLayer(...)
layer.input_var.tag.test_value = np.random.randn(*layer.shape).astype(layer.input_var.dtype)
```

> This cannot just be done in one global call to get_output, because the information is needed before the layer structure is complete.

I think dynamic padding/cropping should be done by a Layer, using symbolic case distinctions. When do you need to set constructor parameters of the next layer depending on the symbolic shape (and *how* can you actually do so, if you've got the symbolic shape only)? Do you have a concrete use case?

> Implementing the cache would lead to a more complicated code (note though that the final user would not be affected or even aware of it)

There may be some gotchas around the following use:
```python
l_in = InputLayer((1,2,3))
l_2 = DenseLayer(...)
l_3 = FancyLayer that chooses some parameter depending on l_2.get_output()
out = l_3.get_output(T.tensor3('x'))
```
Now l_3 might depend on both l_in.input_var and the new variable. How'd you fix that? Cloning l_3.get_output() with replacement instead of calling with the new variable?
When would you start to precompute expressions? Whenever a layer is added or only when get_output() is called? What if get_output() with default arguments fails because some layer class chooses to alter its behaviour in a way that requires certain keyword arguments?

> (note though that the final user would not be affected or even aware of it)

Second note on this point: In our design goals, what you call ""final user"" is not just somebody importing Lasagne and creating some straightforward network with it, but somebody possibly versed in Theano using Lasagne as a basis for experiments. It's vital that Lasagne not only has an easy interface, but also an easy implementation. Making the internals too complicated does affect the final user.

I'm still not convinced, but still open to going into more detail!",{},,User,False
