15409,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-19 14:40:57+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,122280353,211954226,"> While you're discussing this, is there a reason why MergeLayer needs to be a special subclass, could support for multiple incomings be rolled into the Layer superclass, and a single incoming just be a special case of it?

I think the main reason is what we called ""Restraint"" (for the lack of a better word) in our [design principles](http://lasagne.readthedocs.org/en/latest/user/development.html#philosophy). The most common type of layer only has a single input, and a single incoming layer. It should be straightforward to read and write such implementations, without having to know or care that there could be other cases. I.e., when implementing a dense layer, users should not have to check that they receive a single input only, or are linked to a single incoming layer only, or have to unwrap the incoming data in some way.
But you're right that inheritance could probably be turned around such that `Layer` is a special case that has a single incoming layer, and `InputLayer` is a special case that has no incoming layers (although we still need to differentiate that from the case of a free-floating layer such as `DenseLayer((10, 20), 30)`). However, this would require additional wrapper methods such that implementers of a `Layer` subclass can access `self.input_layer` instead of `self.input_layers[0]` and their `get_output_for(inputs, **kwargs)` does not have to unwrap `inputs[0]`. This might be more difficult to follow than what we have now (although I'm also unhappy that `InputLayer` and `MergeLayer` break the `Layer` interface).
A further complication is that Lasagne is already in use, and changing old design decisions is difficult without breaking code. Maybe we should collect ideas for a major (non-compatible) release somewhere.

Is there a way to fix things in a straightforward and backwards-compatible way? Maybe add a new `BaseLayer` base class that allows `incoming` to be any collection of layers/shapes (list, dictionary, or plain) and have `self.input_shape` and `input` in `get_output_for(input)` match this structure? Then have `Layer` ensure that `incoming` is a plain layer or shape, `MergeLayer` ensure that it is a plain list, and `InputLayer` ensure that it is a plain shape? We'd still need to have MergeLayer and InputLayer inherit from Layer (which is ugly) to ensure backwards compatibility (people expecting `isinstance(x, Layer)` to catch all kinds of layers), but they could just override whatever Layer does.",{},,User,False
