15635,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-08 19:31:55+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,2498805,rhelmot,12520807,angr,286790494,356071157,"Hello! First, thank you for pointing out the inconsistency in the docs - I've updated it to fix the deprecated code.

Your issue has nothing to do with the way you're hooking, and everything to do with angr's poor support for windows programs - or rather, the serious issues with trying to do blind binary analysis on files compiled with msvc. At least when I compile and run this code, angr spins off into oblivion with a state explosion trying to execute the initializer functions - we don't start execution from main, we start from the entry point. Between the amount of code that's statically linked into the executable (as opposed to linux's standard `__libc_start_main`) and the horrifying reliance on dynamic loading  (api-ms-win-core-synch-l1-2-0.dll anyone?), it's a nightmare even getting to main.

Additionally, there is the serious issue with the stdcall calling convention, and when we don't know how many arguments a given function is supposed to take, and the real implementation of the function isn't available to run, the stack will be unbalanced and emulation will fail. @schieb was working on a library of common functions and their arguments to add to angr to solve this problem, but I haven't heard from him recently.

Long story short: you're going to need to hold angr's hand a lot more aggressively if you want any sort of analysis like this to work. This will involve one or both of implementing simprocedure stubs for problematic library functions and providing more specific analysis goals than ""symbolically execute from the entry point.""

You can debug things like this by either stepping until you see a symbolic branch (`simgr.step(until=lambda lsm: len(lsm.active) != 1)`) or just ^Cing the emulation and examining what's in the simgr at any given point.",{},OWNER,User,False
