15709,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-25 22:32:32+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,5368500,hamishwillee,12973369,dronekit,136239418,189013975,"FYI, I also updated the release notes in the docs with https://github.com/dronekit/dronekit-python/pull/590 and the notes on the DK discuss forum.",{},,User,False
15710,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-12 23:48:59+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,5368500,hamishwillee,12973369,dronekit,114713511,156273535,"@atomictom  keeping state ""right"" is pretty tough when asynchronous systems. 

As in https://github.com/dronekit/dronekit-python/issues/397#issuecomment-155938601 above, my feeling is that callbacks really are best only be used for global monitoring and handling  of system status or logging. Any sort of initialisation/movement/startup should be done synchronously, checking for success before proceeding.

So in your case I'd have a global observer on LAND mode (or RTL) which turns either exits the script or returns it to a safe state. The re-initialisation code would be part of the start of a normal initialization cycle. Of course this may well be much easier to say than do :-)

Generally though, if you can do this it should simplify any checking you might otherwise need to do in each of your individual functions.

That said, I think it is very good advice ""not to assume state"" and to consider whether there are conditions under which a command will not work. Also to take care when assuming that callbacks will be called in a timely manner.

* Does any of the above thinking seem mad?
* Is there any way we could improve the architecture to reduce these issues?

Thanks very much!",{},,User,False
