16488,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-11 16:18:17+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,255883042,335864822,"@hanno-arm, thanks for working with us to address this issue.

Application data is only sent in response to calling `mbedtls_ssl_handshake()` and the ssl context `state` member is set to `MBEDTLS_SSL_HANDSHAKE_OVER` after the call.  The corresponding code is here: https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/src/core/meshcop/dtls.cpp#L402",{},OWNER,User,False
16491,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-02 06:58:36+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,17729664,abtink,16142269,openthread,211299684,283572878,"While it's true that both inbound and outbound spinel frames will have similar maximum len,  in NCP implementation we have optimized the way we manage the outbound/tx buffer so that we can use a smaller buffer size.

The `NcpFrameBuffer` (which is used for outbound spinel frames) is designed in a way that it can embed an `otMessage` without requiring to copy the actual content (payload) of the `otMessage`. This way we can use a much smaller buffer while still storing and sending larger spinel frames.

For an inbound spinel message, we need a buffer large enough to hold a maximum size spinel frame (which itself can contain an IPv6 message payload).



",{},,User,False
