16818,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-12 17:53:02+00:00,63484632,facebookresearch/fastText,1716488,cpuhrsch,16943930,facebookresearch,233758930,314846751,"Hello @EmilStenstrom,

Thank you for the detailed description of your problem!  The segfault does indeed appear to be caused by this very high learning rate and I can reproduce it on my side. When setting a more reasonable learning rate (such as 0.01), the training proceeds and finishes successfully. We'll investigate this issue in more detail.

For what it's worth, related to your first issue, most of the memory usage comes from either the input or output parameter matrix. The input matrix for supervised training will be the number of words plus the size of the bucket, which is 2M by default, times the dimensionality (-dim). So, for your first example, you'll need to allocate one matrix (floats) of size (2445360 + 2000000) x 100. The output matrix will need to be able to produce a prediction for each label. So it would be of size 100 x 3787938. These are rather large. To influence the number of words, set a higher number for the '-minCount' option. To change the number of buckets (bins for hashing of non-words) use the -bucket flag. To influence the number of labels use the -minLabelCount option.

Thanks,
Christian",{},,User,False
16845,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-17 17:47:15+00:00,3277149,pyFFTW/pyFFTW,11278668,bwohlberg,16965121,pyFFTW,275182549,352272671,"Good point. This test was written before we discovered the alignment connection, but yes, it does seem to reliably fail when the issue is present. This is probably why two sets of ``rfttn`` calls were needed; if I were to redesign the test with the knowledge of the role of alignment, it would probably be possible to reduce it to a single set of ``rfftn`` calls.",{},NONE,User,False
16846,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-07 18:15:13+00:00,3277149,pyFFTW/pyFFTW,6528957,grlee77,16965121,pyFFTW,154101080,292612204,"As far as I could tell there are not tests of N dimensional transforms where the number of axes transformed are fewer than N-1.

See the explict numpy fftn interface test shapes here:
https://github.com/pyFFTW/pyFFTW/blob/a5be2182046e18f6f2d06d9becb3b00c138b1821/test/test_pyfftw_numpy_interface.py#L725-L733

It should only be a couple lines modified to add a case there with 3D data and only 1 axis transformed or 4D data with 2 axes transformed.  @ferdinandvanwyk or @davidbrough1 :  are either of you interested in making a PR for this? probably worth adding that case to the `builders` tests as well

",{},,User,False
