16892,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-24 17:13:01+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,2812720,tleonhardt,17161025,python-cmd2,237456789,339064108,"@mgiaco 
Hi Mathias,

As long as you don't have any thread synchronization issues, what you are doing should work fine.  With the way you are doing it you may get two commands running at the same time, one from the serial line via ``onecmd_plus_hooks`` and one from the ``cmdloop``.  If there are any data structures in your application which need protection for multithreaded access, you may want to add something like an ``RLock``, but other than that I think what you are doing is fine.  

If one of the commands which could be run over the serial line is a ``load`` to kick off a script, then I would recommend using ``runcmds_plus_hooks`` instead of ``onecmd_plus_hooks`` because that method will appropriately deal with running commands which ``load`` places in the cmdqueue before returning.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
