17636,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-22 08:16:47+00:00,66776276,python-social-auth/social-core,5492960,ZiFFeL1992,21279195,python-social-auth,323937415,390903337,"`state` can be passed as a query param, in some cases as CSRF and in some others as an identifier to match someone before doing oauth and after doing it.

In my case I use Google Oauth 2, if I pass `state` to login:

`mydomain.com/login/?state=randomString`

I hope that the response in the callback request contains an `?state=randomString`.

But [this method](https://github.com/python-social-auth/social-core/blob/2313aa29b49dfbdcca3a2d8601161f23c4d1bae8/social_core/backends/oauth.py#L54) forces the library to create it's own state (and ignores if I explicitly pass one) for each user which is fine for 99% of cases but is not when you want to identify an user before and after login for tracking purposes (for example).",{},NONE,User,False
