18040,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-20 09:48:09+00:00,34138622,jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets,30594293,BenjaPH,25869250,jupyter-widgets,266781052,338160108,"Ok, i think i have understood now the problem better. The solution that @pbugnion gave me completely solve my problem, but my confusion came up when i coded it in a slightly different order. Then, when the options set must be changed in any place of the code i will adopt the following pattern,
```
options_copy = dropdown.options.copy()    # obtain a copy of the object ""different id"" with the current options
options_copy['ZZZ'] = 9                                # add/modify new options
dropdown.options = options_copy               # reassign the updated new object
```
So the dropdown widget options assignment (new object id) trigger the observed value change event and internally pass the redundant check that the object contents are really different from the old one. Thus, modifies the _options_labels attribute.
i don't know if this reasoning is more or less correct but it works fine.
Thank you both for these great answers and please don't eliminate the dictionary for the options, this solution is a very easy workaround.",{},NONE,User,False
