18358,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-28 09:12:43+00:00,107225370,velocyto-team/velocyto.py,4210138,gioelelm,32676609,velocyto-team,353641781,416510451,"Hi,

First of all, thank you for sharing your concerns. This was very useful since I hadn't had the opportunity to stop and reflect on the implication of their preprocessing. I, maybe naively, thought that 10x wouldn't change the value of the NH tag (multiple mapping tag). If I understand correctly that this is what they are doing, it sounds a controversial thing to do, as it obfuscates the real output of the aligner.

I think that your concerns are well founded, in the sense that it would be preferable to run on a bam file that has not been modified in such a way. I think some adjustments should be done to address it to ensure higher accuracy of exonic and intronic estimation. 

Anyways, consistently with the conservative spirit of the rest of the pipeline, what I would do to address this problem is just to exclude the multiple mapping from the counting. I wouldn't flag those mappings as intronic, as I expect that overinflating intronic read counts will introduce major errors velocity estimation than overinflating the exonic counts.

In that sense, your observation hints to the fact that, right now, the quantification of the exonic fraction might be biassed (upper bound ~15%) when compared to a more conservative estimate obtained by excluding multiple mappings.

My solution would be a fix to the source of cellranger pipeline to keep the NH flag to a value > 1. Then the pipeline will do its job correctly.",{},MEMBER,User,False
