18515,IssueCommentEvent,2011-12-12 23:22:21+00:00,1446474,pypa/virtualenv,68801,dougn,647025,pypa,676626,3114902,"The real problem here is how windows tries to find and load the proper DLL.
The fallover is as follows:

1. same directory as the .exe
2. the registry DLL load paths
3. the env PATH

With the installed python it will find it along side python.exe in the installed directory.
When python is installed for 'all users' then the DLL will be found in the windows system directory via the registry.
If you only have 1 python installed and it is on your PATH then it will find it that way.
Otherwise you get this or another error.
This is really bad if you have both 32bit and 64bit versions of python installed, as you will only be able to create virtualenv's for one or the other (which ever was installed last.)

The real solution is to always copy the pythonXX.dll from the install location along with the .exe
",{},,,
